CVE (Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures) is a publicly available, standardized database that catalogs known cybersecurity vulnerabilities in software and hardware.
Each flaw receives a unique identifier, allowing security teams, vendors, and researchers worldwide to speak the exact same language when identifying, sharing, and patching security risks.
<i>How It Works & Its Uses</i>
Universal Standard: It prevents confusion so that when multiple security tools or vendors discuss a threat, they reference the identical identifier.
Vulnerability Tracking: Records detail the exact coding mistake or system weakness (often classified via CWE) and rank the danger using the CVSS (0.0 to 10.0 scale).
Patch Management: Organizations use the CVE List and the U.S. National Vulnerability Database (NVD) to prioritize system updates and protect against active attacks.
